It sounds like you want the [observer pattern][1], when an event occurs somewhere you want your first JFrame to react to it. 

**This solution requires Java 7 or later**

It would make sense to have a separate class maintain the state of your settings. This implementation is a [singleton][2] which will work well enough for your implementation, although as you learn there will be better options.

```java
public class Settings {
   public enum ScreenMode {
      LIGHT,
      DARK
   }

   private static Settings settings;
   private ScreenMode screenMode = ScreenMode.LIGHT;
   private final PropertyChangeSupport pcs;

   /**
    * Private constructor to force singleton pattern
    */
   private Settings() {
      pcs = new PropertyChangeSupport(this);
   }

   /**
    * Get the singleton instance of Settings.
    * When you learn dependency injection, prefer that.
    */
   public static Settings getSettings() {
      if (settings == null) {
         settings = new Settings();
      }
      return settings;
   }

   public void addPropertyChangeListener(PropertyChangeListener pcl) {
      pcs.addPropertyChangeListener(pcl);
   }

   public void setScreenMode(ScreenMode mode) {
      pcs.firePropertyChange(&quot;screen_mode&quot;, this.screenMode, mode);
      this.screenMode = mode;
   }
}
```

This settings object will allow any `PropertyChangeListener` to subscribe to it and be notified whenever a property changes. JFrame 1 can become a `PropertyChangeListener` by implementing the interface and subscribing to the `Settings.addPropertyChangeListener()` method.

```java
public class SpiceWars4 extends JFrame implements PropertyChangeListener {

   public SpiceWars4() { 
      // Frame-Initialisierung
      super();
      Settings.getSettings().addPropertyChangeListener(this); // Subscribe
      ...
   }

   ...

   @Override
   public void propertyChange(PropertyChangeEvent evt) {
      if (evt.getPropertyName().equals(&quot;screen_mode&quot;)) {
         Settings.ScreenMode mode = (Settings.ScreenMode) evt.getNewValue();
         switch (mode) {
            case LIGHT:
               // Called when screen mode is changed from dark to light
               break;
            case DARK:
               // Called when screen mode is changed from light to dark
               break;
         }
      }
   }

   ...
}
```

Then the code from JFrame 2 that actually sets the property when you click the button:

```java
Settings.getSettings().setScreenMode(Settings.ScreenMode.DARK);
```

Setting the screen mode fires a property change event that will execute the `propertyChange(PropertyEvent)` method of all subscribers (JFrame 1). The event can then be handled or ignored as needed.

  [1]: https://www.baeldung.com/java-observer-pattern
  [2]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singleton_pattern

